


# The Weight of a Cloud

Elena hadn't spoken to her mother in three years. Not since the argument about the wedding — the one that ended with slammed doors and words neither of them meant.

"It's not that bad," her friend Marcus said, handing her a coffee. "You'll come around."

"You're exaggerating," Elena replied. "It *is* that bad. She never supported me. Not once."

But at night, when the apartment was quiet and her head sank into the pillow, the silence felt heavier than any argument. She missed the Sunday calls. She missed the way her mother said her name — like it was the most important word she knew.

Then one Tuesday morning, the phone rang. It was her aunt.

"Your mother is in the hospital, Elena."

She drove there faster than she should have. When she walked into the room, her mother looked small in the bed — like a cloud that had lost its shape and drifted close to the ground.

"Elena," her mother whispered, and there it was — that way of saying her name, like it held the whole world.

"I'm here, Mom."

"I'm sorry," her mother said, her hand trembling as she reached out. "I was wrong. About everything."

Elena took her hand and held it tight. "Me too."

In that moment, Elena understood something she had been running from: love is not a weakness or a burden. It is the thing that gives everything else its weight and meaning. Without it, every victory is hollow, every freedom is loneliness. She had spent three years protecting her pride, and all it had given her was silence.

Love doesn't demand perfection. It only asks that you show up — before it's too late.

Her mother recovered. And Elena never let a day pass without calling.

Because a life without love is just a pillow with nothing to rest on it. [end of text]


